#week-title("Three", "The Personal Tree of Life Map")

=== Core Teaching

The Tree of Life is not merely a reference diagram — it is a meditation object
and a working system for self-knowledge. This week the student begins to build
a personal relationship with the Tree: mapping their own character, their
alchemical work, and their inner experience onto the ten sephiroth.

The alchemical question that the Tree makes visible is the same question
Paracelsus asks of every patient: *what is the constitutional balance?* Where
does force concentrate too heavily? Where is deficiency visible? The physician
who can answer this for the patient — and the practitioner who can answer it
for themselves — has the diagnostic foundation for genuine alchemical work.

*The Pillars.* The Tree is arranged on three pillars:

- *The Pillar of Severity (left):* Binah, Geburah, Hod — the contracting,
  forming, analytical principle. Saturn, Mars, Mercury. This is the Salt
  principle in its vertical expression: the fixing, limiting, structuring force.
- *The Pillar of Mercy (right):* Chokmah, Chesed, Netzach — the expanding,
  generative, creative principle. Zodiac/Stars, Jupiter, Venus. This is the
  Sulphur principle in its vertical expression: the opening, multiplying force.
- *The Middle Pillar:* Kether, Daath, Tiphereth, Yesod, Malkuth — the
  balancing central current. The Sun at Tiphereth, the Moon at Yesod. This is
  the Mercury principle as the reconciling and animating force between the poles.

A student who lives predominantly on the Pillar of Severity in their work
(methodical, restricting, critical, never beginning a new preparation without
extensive analysis) needs to consciously engage the right pillar. One who lives
on the Pillar of Mercy (enthusiastic, constantly beginning, rarely completing,
generous to excess) needs the left.

*Placing the Work on the Tree.* Locate each major element of your current work
on the Tree:
- Your sealed Plant Stone digestion → Binah (the long, fixed work)
- Your water preparation → Yesod (the lunar vehicle)
- Your understanding of the three principles as philosophy → Hod (Mercurial
  analysis)
- Your direct laboratory perception during a vigil → Netzach (Venusian feeling)
- Your intention behind the Work → Kether or Chesed (will and generosity)

=== Topics This Week

- The three pillars: Severity, Mercy, and the Middle Pillar
- Pillar analysis as constitutional diagnosis
- Placing the current Work on the Tree: sphere by sphere
- Identifying personal imbalances through the pillar system

#inner-work[
  *Drawing Your Personal Tree*

  Draw the Tree of Life by hand in your journal (or Tarot journal). Label each
  sphere with its name, number, planet, and metal.

  Then make a second copy of the diagram and, on this copy, write within each
  sphere one or two words describing how that sphere manifests in your life or
  Work right now. Kether: what is your originating impulse? Binah: what is the
  most fixed or limiting factor? Tiphereth: where do you feel most centred and
  solar?

  Leave Daath (the invisible sphere of Knowledge on the Middle Pillar) blank
  unless something arises spontaneously — this sphere is not assigned by
  intellectual effort.
]

